2","1160":"1160","Chetwynd,Shropshire,England.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Chetwynd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chatwin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatwin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from a place in Shropshire called Chetwynd, from the Old English personal name <i>Ceatta</i> + Old English <i>(ge)wind</i> ‘winding ascent’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"John I de Chetwynd was born about 1132, in Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Adam Chetwynd. He had at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1132–":"umbes 1132–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1158–1210":"1158–1210","–Male":"Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","about 1132":"umbes 1132","1160":"1160","Chetwynd,Shropshire,England.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1132–":"noin 1132–Kuollut","1132–Male":"1132–Kuollut","1158–1210":"1158–1210","–Male":"Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","about 1132":"noin 1132","1160":"1160","Chetwynd,Shropshire,England.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1132–":"environ 1132–Décédé","1132–Male":"1132–Décédé","1158–1210":"1158–1210","–Male":"Décédé","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","about 1132":"environ 1132","1160":"1160","Chetwynd,Shropshire,England.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"John I de Chetwynd est né environ 1132, à Chetwynd, Shropshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, fils de Adam Chetwynd. Il a eu au moins 3 fils."},"de":{"about 1132–":"um 1132–Verstorben","1132–Male":"1132–Verstorben","1158–1210":"1158–1210","–Male":"Verstorben","1160–Male":"1160–Verstorben","1158":"1158","1210":"1210","1132":"1132","about 1132":"um 1132","1160":"1160","Chetwynd,Shropshire,England.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, Unite